class Solution:
    def findMin(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        low, high = 0, len(nums) - 1
        while low < high:
            mid = (low + high) // 2
            if nums[mid] > nums[high]:
                low = mid + 1
            elif nums[mid] < nums[high]:
                high = mid
            else:
                high -= 1
        return nums[low]

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
Use a variant of binary search to find the smallest element in a rotated sorted array that may contain duplicates.

Maintain two pointers `low` and `high`. At each step:
- Compute mid.
- If nums[mid] > nums[high], the minimum must be in the right half (rotation point is after mid).
- If nums[mid] < nums[high], the minimum is in the left half (including mid).
- If nums[mid] == nums[high], we cannot decide, so shrink the search space by decrementing high (this handles duplicates).

The loop continues until low == high, at which point nums[low] is the minimum element.

This algorithm guarantees correctness even with duplicates, though the worst-case time complexity becomes O(n) when all elements are equal.

Time Complexity: O(log n) on average, O(n) worst case
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
